        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Burial of Moses.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>By Nebo&#39;s lonely mountain&#44;<lb/>
            On this side of Jordan&#39;s wave&#44;<lb/>
            In a vale in the land of Moab&#44;<lb/>
            There lieth a lonely grave&#59;<lb/>
            And no man dug that sepulchre&#44;<lb/>
            And no man saw it e&#39;er&#44;<lb/>
            For the angels of God upturned the sud<lb/>
            And laid the dead man there.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>This was the grandest funeral<lb/>
            That ever passed on earth&#44;<lb/>
            But no man heard the tramping&#44;<lb/>
            Or saw the train go forth&#44;<lb/>
            Silently as the day light<lb/>
            Comes when the night is done&#44;<lb/>
            And the crimson streak on ocean&#39;s cheek<lb/>
            Glows into the great red sun.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Silently as the spring time<lb/>
            Its crowd of verdure weaves&#44;<lb/>
            And all the trees on all the hills<lb/>
            Open their thousand leaves.<lb/>
            So&#44; without sound of music&#44;<lb/>
            Or voice of him that wept&#44;<lb/>
            Silently down from the mountain&#39;s crown&#44;<lb/>
            The great procession swept.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>Perchance the bald old eagle&#44;<lb/>
            On dark Bethbeor&#39;s height&#44;<lb/>
            Down from his rocky eyrie&#44;<lb/>
            Looked in the wondrous sight&#58;<lb/>
            Perchance on the lion stalking<lb/>
            Avoids the sacred spot&#45;&#45;<lb/>
            For beast and bird have seen and heard<lb/>
            That which man knoweth not.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Amid the noblest of the land<lb/>
            Men lay the sage to rest&#44;<lb/>
            And give the bard an honest place<lb/>
            With costly marbles dressed&#58;<lb/>
            In the great minster transept&#58;<lb/>
            Where lights like glories fall&#44;<lb/>
            And the sweet choir sings and the organ rings<lb/>
            Along the emblazoned wall.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>This was the bravest warrior<lb/>
            That ever buckled sword&#45;&#45;<lb/>
            This was the most gifted poet<lb/>
            That ever breathed a word&#58;<lb/>
            And never earth&#39;s philosopher<lb/>
            Traced with his good pen&#44;<lb/>
            On the deathless page&#44; truth half so sage<lb/>
            As he wrote down for men.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>And had he not high honor&#44;<lb/>
            The hill side for his pall&#44;<lb/>
            To lie in state&#44; whilst angels wait&#44;<lb/>
            With stars for taper&#39;s talb&#45;&#45;<lb/>
            And the dark rock pines like the tossing plumes<lb/>
            Over his bier to wave&#44;<lb/>
            And God&#39;s own hand in that lonely land<lb/>
            To lay him in the grave&#33;<lb/></p>
            
            <p>Oh&#33; lonely tomb in Moab&#39;s land&#44;<lb/>
            Oh&#33; dark Bethbeor&#39;s hill&#44;<lb/>
            Speak to those curious hearts of ours<lb/>
            And teach them to be still.<lb/>
            God hath his mysteries of grace&#44;<lb/>
            Thoughts that we cannot tell&#44;<lb/>
            And he hides them deep&#44; like the secret sleep.<lb/>
            Of Him he loved so well.<lb/></p>
            <p>Copied for Miss Cohen<lb/>
            by L Buniand<lb/>
                December 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1870<lb/></p>
            
                <pb n="5"/>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                546. No. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/>
                Philadelphia.<lb/></p>

